## File Modification Rules

### ‚úÖ OK to modify:

- Source code files (.ts, .tsx, .js, etc.)
- Configuration files (tsconfig.json, package.json, etc.)
- Documentation (.md files)
- Tests

### ‚ö†Ô∏è Be careful with:

- Environment files (.env, .env.production)
- Build configuration (webpack, tsconfig)
- CI/CD configuration (.github/workflows)

### ‚ùå Don't modify:

- Git hooks without explicit request
- .gitignore without understanding implications
- Other agents' or users' work without consent

## Commit Message Format

When suggesting commit messages, use conventional commits:

```
type(scope): description

feat(auth): add JWT token refresh
fix(ui): resolve button alignment issue
docs(readme): update installation steps
refactor(api): simplify error handling
test(utils): add edge case tests
chore(deps): update dependencies
```

## Pull Request Guidelines

If you need to create a PR:

1. Always push to a branch first (user does this)
2. Never auto-merge
3. Provide clear PR description
4. List all changes made
5. Explain testing approach

## Transparency

Always tell the user:

- What you're about to do
- Why you're doing it
- What could go wrong
- How to undo it if needed

